  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "88649b4c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Hypothesis Testing of Health Insurance Data\n",
    "## Introduction\n",
    "The focus of this notebook is to describe the procedure for performing hypothesis testing and statistical analysis of a complex dataset, like the data contained in the Health Insurance dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Description of the Data:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Age** - This is an integer indicating the age of the primary beneficiary (excluding those above 64 years, since they are generally covered by the government).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Sex** - This is the policy holder's gender, either male or female.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- **BMI** - This is the body mass index (BMI), which provides a sense of how over or under-weight a person is relative to their height. BMI is equal to weight (in kilograms) divided by height (in meters) squared. An ideal BMI is within the range of 18.5 to 24.9.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Children** - This is an integer indicating the number of children / dependents covered by the insurance plan.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Smoker** - This is yes or no depending on whether the insured regularly smokes tobacco.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Region** - This is the beneficiary's place of residence in the U.S., divided into four geographic regions - northeast, southeast, southwest, or northwest.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Charges** - Individual medical costs billed to health insurance.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Key Activities:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Explore the dataset and extract insights using Exploratory Data Analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Prove statistically whether or not the medical claims made by people who smoke are greater than those who do not.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Prove statistically whether the BMI of females is different from that of males.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Prove statistically whether or not the proportion of smokers is significantly different across regions.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Prove statistically whether the mean BMI of women with no children, one child, and two children the same."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "27a474b4",

    "fig.suptitle(\"SPREAD OF DATA\", fontsize=18, fontweight='bold');\n",
    "fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.92);\n",
    "fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5, wspace=0.4);\n",
    "\n",
    "#load plots into subplots, and set plot parameters\n",
    "ax0 = fig.add_subplot(3, 3, 1);\n",
    "sns.distplot(dat['age'], ax=ax0, color='dodgerblue');\n",
    "ax0.axvline(dat['age'].quantile(q=0.25),color='green',linestyle='--',label='25% Quartile');\n",
    "ax0.axvline(dat['age'].mean(),color='red',linestyle='--',label='Mean');\n",
    "ax0.axvline(dat['age'].median(),color='black',linestyle='--',label='Median');\n",
    "ax0.axvline(dat['age'].quantile(q=0.75),color='blue',linestyle='--',label='75% Quartile');\n",
    "ax0.text(77, 0.044, 'skewness: {}' .format(str(round(dat['age'].skew(),3))), ha='right', va='center', size=11)\n",
    "ax0.set_title('Age', fontdict=axtitle_dict);\n",
    "ax0.set_xlabel('Age [yrs]', fontdict=axlab_dict);\n",
    "ax0.legend(fontsize=10);\n",
    "\n",
    "ax1 = fig.add_subplot(3, 3, 2);\n",
    "sns.barplot(x=list(gender[0]), y=list(gender[1]), ax=ax1, color='coral');\n",
    "ax1.text(0.2, 600, '{}%' .format(str(round(gender[1][0]/sum(gender[1])*100,1))), ha='right', va='center', size=13, \n",
    "                                                                                            fontdict={'weight': 'bold'})\n",
    "ax1.text(1.2, 610, '{}%' .format(str(round(gender[1][1]/sum(gender[1])*100,1))), ha='right', va='center', size=13, \n",
    "                                                                                            fontdict={'weight': 'bold'})\n",
    "ax1.set_title('Gender', fontdict=axtitle_dict);\n",
    "ax1.set_xlabel('Gender', fontdict=axlab_dict);\n",
    "ax1.set_ylabel('Count', fontdict=axlab_dict);\n",
    "\n",

    "ax2.set_xlabel('Body Mass Index', fontdict=axlab_dict);\n",
    "ax2.legend(fontsize=10);\n",
    "\n",

    "sns.countplot(dat['children'], ax=ax3, color='limegreen');\n",
    "ax3.set_title('No. of Children', fontdict=axtitle_dict);\n",
    "ax3.set_xlabel('Integer Categorical', fontdict=axlab_dict);\n",

    "ax6.set_xlabel('Charges [$USD]', fontdict=axlab_dict);\n",

    "Here's a step-by-step explanation of the above code:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Fontdicts: Two fontdicts (axtitle_dict and axlab_dict) are created to define the formatting of text in the figure. These fontdicts specify properties such as the font family, color, weight, and size.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Figure creation: A figure is created using plt.figure(figsize=[16,12]), specifying the size of the figure as 16 inches by 12 inches.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Figure title: The title of the figure is set using fig.suptitle(\"SPREAD OF DATA\", fontsize=18, fontweight='bold'). It sets the main title of the figure with a font size of 18 and bold font weight.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "4. Subplot adjustments: The spacing between subplots is adjusted using fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.92) to provide space for the figure title. Additionally, fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5, wspace=0.4) sets the vertical and horizontal spacing between subplots.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Subplot creation and plotting:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Nine subplots (ax0 to ax8) are created using fig.add_subplot(3, 3, n), where 'n' represents the position of the subplot in the 3x3 grid.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Various seaborn plots (such as sns.distplot, sns.barplot, and sns.countplot) are used to visualize different aspects of the data in each subplot.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Each subplot is customized with titles, labels, and additional elements such as vertical lines, text annotations, and legends to provide insights and highlight key statistics.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "6. Customizations:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Fontdicts (axtitle_dict and axlab_dict) are used to set the font properties for titles, x-axis labels, y-axis labels, and text annotations.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Colors are specified for the plots using color names like 'dodgerblue', 'coral', 'peru', 'limegreen', 'gold', 'teal', and 'orchid'.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The code generates a 3x3 grid of subplots, each displaying a different visualization of the data, including distribution plots, bar plots, and count plots. The code also adds annotations and statistical indicators to provide additional information about the data."
   ]

   "id": "27f79656",

   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x1000 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#create fontdict for axis labels\n",
    "axlab2 = {'family': 'serif',\n",
    "              'color': 'black',\n",
    "              'weight': 'bold',\n",
    "              'size': 16\n",
    "         }\n",
    "#create subplot layout\n",
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=[10,10]);\n",
    "grid = plt.GridSpec(6, 1, wspace=0.3, hspace=1.2);\n",
    "x = ['age', 'bmi', 'children', 'charges'];\n",
    "col = ['forestgreen','dodgerblue','goldenrod', 'coral'];\n",
    "\n",
    "#loop to populate boxplots within subplots\n",
    "for i in np.arange(0,4):\n",
    "    for j in np.arange(0,1): \n",
    "        exec(f'ax{i}{j} = plt.subplot(grid[i,j]);')\n",
    "        exec(f'sns.boxplot(x=dat[x[{i}]], ax=ax{i}{j}, color=col[{i}]);')\n",
    "        exec(f'ax{i}{j}.set_title(x[{i}], fontdict=axlab2);')\n",
    "        exec(f'ax{i}{j}.set_xlabel(\"\", fontdict=axlab2);')\n",
    "        exec(f'a{i} = ax{i}{j}.axvline(dat[x[{i}]].mean(),color= \"red\", linestyle=\"--\", label=\"mean\")')\n",
    "        exec(f'b{i} = ax{i}{j}.axvline(dat[x[{i}]].mean()+ 3 * dat[x[{i}]].std(),color= \"orange\", linestyle=\"--\", \\\n",
    "                                                                                                        label=\"3sigma\")')\n",
    "        exec(f'ax{i}{j}.axvline(max([dat[x[{i}]].mean()- 3 * dat[x[{i}]].std(), 0]),color= \"orange\", linestyle=\"--\")')\n",
    "        exec(f'c{i} = ax{i}{j}.axvline(dat[x[{i}]].mean()+ 2 * dat[x[{i}]].std(),color= \"slategrey\", linestyle=\"--\", \\\n",
    "                                                                                                        label=\"2sigma\")')\n",
    "        exec(f'ax{i}{j}.axvline(max([dat[x[{i}]].mean()- 2 * dat[x[{i}]].std(), 0]),color= \"slategrey\", linestyle=\"--\")')\n",
    "        plt.xticks(fontsize=14);\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.legend([a0, c0, b0], ['mean','2sigma','3sigma'], loc='upper center', bbox_to_anchor=(0.9, 9.4), fontsize=14)        \n",
    "fig.show();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c0b5d675",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The above code creates a subplot layout with boxplots for four variables ('age', 'bmi', 'children', 'charges'). Here's a step-by-step explanation of the code:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Fontdict creation: A fontdict axlab2 is created to define the formatting of axis labels. It specifies properties such as the font family, color, weight, and size.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Figure creation: A figure is created using plt.figure(figsize=[10,10]), specifying the size of the figure as 10 inches by 10 inches.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Grid specification: A grid layout with 6 rows and 1 column is created using grid = plt.GridSpec(6, 1, wspace=0.3, hspace=1.2). This grid will be used to assign subplots to different positions.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "4. Variables and colors: Two lists are defined: x containing the names of the variables to be plotted, and col containing the corresponding colors for each variable.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Subplot creation and plotting:\n",
    "\n",
    "- A nested loop is used to populate the subplots within the grid.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- The exec function is used to dynamically create variable names for the subplots (e.g., ax01, ax11, etc.) and boxplot-related variables (e.g., a0, b0, c0, etc.).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- For each subplot, a boxplot is created using sns.boxplot with the corresponding variable from the x list and the specified color from the col list.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Titles for each subplot are set using ax{i}{j}.set_title(x[{i}], fontdict=axlab2), where {i} represents the index of the variable in the x list.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- X-axis labels are set to empty strings using ax{i}{j}.set_xlabel(\"\", fontdict=axlab2).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Vertical lines representing mean, 2-sigma, and 3-sigma are added to the boxplots using ax{i}{j}.axvline.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Font size for x-axis tick labels is set using plt.xticks(fontsize=14).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "6. Legend creation: A legend is created using plt.legend and includes the vertical lines representing mean, 2-sigma, and 3-sigma from the first subplot. The legend is positioned using the loc parameter and adjusted using the bbox_to_anchor parameter. The font size is set using the fontsize parameter.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "7. Display the figure: fig.show() is called to display the figure.\n",
    "\n",
    "The code generates a set of subplots, each containing a boxplot for one of the variables. The boxplots show the distribution of each variable, with horizontal lines representing the median and quartiles. The vertical lines indicate the mean, 2-sigma, and 3-sigma values for the variable. A legend is added to explain the meaning of the vertical lines."
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "1c5f6bb2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "The following features in the data are significantly correlated (-0.5 < coef. > 0.5):\n",
      "                        \n",
      "0   Smok_no     charges\n",
      "1  Smok_yes     charges\n",
      "2  Gen_male  Gen_female\n",
      "3  Smok_yes     Smok_no\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# find which features have significant correlation (-0.5 < coef. > 0.5) \n",
    "blah = np.logical_or(dum_dat.corr()>0.5, dum_dat.corr()<-0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "# disregard identity\n",
    "for i in np.arange(0,len(blah)):\n",
    "    blah.iloc[i,i] = False\n",
    "\n",
    "# create table of correlation relationships by index values\n",
    "corr_val = []\n",
    "for i in np.arange(0,len(blah.iloc[0,:])):\n",
    "    for j in np.arange(0,len(blah.iloc[:,0])):\n",
    "        if blah.iloc[i,j] == True:\n",
    "            corr_val.append([blah.index.values[j], blah.columns.values[i]])\n",
    "\n",
    "# drop rows in table in which relationships are duplicated in table (x vs. y and y vs. x)            \n",
    "x = []\n",
    "for i in np.arange(0,len(corr_val)):\n",
    "    x.append(str(i))\n",
    "corr_val = pd.DataFrame(corr_val, columns=[\"\",\"\"], index=x)\n",
    "del blah, x\n",
    "for i in corr_val.index:\n",
    "    for j in corr_val.index:\n",
    "        if any(corr_val.index == i) == True:\n",
    "            a, b = corr_val.loc[i]\n",
    "            if i != j:\n",
    "                if np.logical_and((corr_val.loc[j][0] == b) == True, (corr_val.loc[j][1] == a) == True) == True:\n",
    "                    corr_val.drop(j, inplace=True);\n",
    "corr_val.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "print('The following features in the data are significantly correlated (-0.5 < coef. > 0.5):\\n {}' .format(corr_val))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "953e8514",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The above code aims to identify which features in the dum_dat dataset have a significant correlation coefficient between -0.5 and 0.5. Here's a step-by-step explanation of the code:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Logical comparison: The code compares the correlation matrix of dum_dat with the condition > 0.5 or < -0.5 using np.logical_or(dum_dat.corr() > 0.5, dum_dat.corr() < -0.5). This creates a boolean matrix (blah) where True indicates that the corresponding correlation coefficient satisfies the condition.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Disregarding identity: The diagonal elements (identity) in the blah matrix are set to False to disregard the correlations of each feature with itself. This is done in a loop using blah.iloc[i, i] = False for each row/column i.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Creating a table of correlation relationships: The code creates an empty list corr_val to store the correlation relationships between features. It then iterates through each element of the blah matrix and checks if it is True. If so, it appends the corresponding feature index values to the corr_val list.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "4. Removing duplicate relationships: The code creates a new index list x to store the index values of the corr_val table. It then converts corr_val to a DataFrame, assigning x as the index and empty column names (two empty strings) for the columns. After that, the code iterates through each row and column index of the corr_val table. If a relationship is found in both directions (x vs. y and y vs. x), it is considered a duplicate and one of them is dropped from the table using corr_val.drop(j, inplace=True).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Resetting the index: The index of the corr_val table is reset using corr_val.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "6. Printing the result: The code prints the list of significantly correlated features using print('The following features in the data are significantly correlated (-0.5 < coef. > 0.5):\\n {}'.format(corr_val)).\n",
    "\n",
    "The result is a table (corr_val) that lists the pairs of features in the dum_dat dataset that have a significant correlation coefficient between -0.5 and 0.5. The table includes one column for each feature in the pair, and each row represents a unique correlation relationship."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "blah = []\n",
    "for i in np.arange(0,len(dat)):\n",
    "        if np.logical_and(dat.loc[i,'children'] == 0, dat.loc[i,'smoker']== 'no'):\n",
    "            blah.append('np_ns')\n",
    "        elif np.logical_and(dat.loc[i,'children'] == 0, dat.loc[i,'smoker']=='yes'):\n",
    "            blah.append('np_sm')\n",
    "        elif np.logical_and(dat.loc[i,'children'] > 0, dat.loc[i,'smoker']=='no'):\n",
    "            blah.append('p_ns')\n",
    "        elif np.logical_and(dat.loc[i,'children'] > 0, dat.loc[i,'smoker']=='yes'):\n",
    "            blah.append('p_sm')\n",
    "a = dat.copy()\n",
    "a['parent_smoke'] = blah"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "636b2a4b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The above code segment creates a new column called 'parent_smoke' in the dat DataFrame based on the values of the 'children' and 'smoker' columns. Here's a step-by-step explanation of the code:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Initialization: An empty list blah is created to store the values for the 'parent_smoke' column.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Iteration: The code iterates through each row of the dat DataFrame using the indices generated by np.arange(0, len(dat)).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Conditional statements: For each row, the code evaluates different conditions using np.logical_and to determine the value of the 'parent_smoke' column. The conditions are as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "- If the value of 'children' is 0 and the value of 'smoker' is 'no', the corresponding value in blah is set to 'np_ns'.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- If the value of 'children' is 0 and the value of 'smoker' is 'yes', the corresponding value in blah is set to 'np_sm'.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- If the value of 'children' is greater than 0 and the value of 'smoker' is 'no', the corresponding value in blah is set to 'p_ns'.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- If the value of 'children' is greater than 0 and the value of 'smoker' is 'yes', the corresponding value in blah is set to 'p_sm'.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "4. Creating a copy: The code creates a copy of the dat DataFrame using a = dat.copy() to avoid modifying the original DataFrame.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Adding a new column: The blah list is assigned to a new column called 'parent_smoke' in the a DataFrame using a['parent_smoke'] = blah.\n",
    "\n",
    "The result is a modified DataFrame a that includes the new 'parent_smoke' column with values based on the conditions specified in the code. The values in the 'parent_smoke' column indicate different combinations of parental smoking status ('np_ns' for non-smoking parents with no children, 'np_sm' for smoking parents with no children, 'p_ns' for non-smoking parents with children, and 'p_sm' for smoking parents with children)."
   ]
  },

    "sw_m = len(dat.loc[np.logical_and(dat['region']=='southwest', np.logical_and(dat['smoker']=='yes', dat['sex']=='male')),:])\n",
    "sw_f = len(dat.loc[np.logical_and(dat['region']=='southwest', np.logical_and(dat['smoker']=='yes', \n",
    "                                                                                                 dat['sex']=='female')),:])\n",
    "se_m = len(dat.loc[np.logical_and(dat['region']=='southeast', np.logical_and(dat['smoker']=='yes', dat['sex']=='male')),:])\n",
    "se_f = len(dat.loc[np.logical_and(dat['region']=='southeast', np.logical_and(dat['smoker']=='yes', \n",
    "                                                                                                dat['sex']=='female')),:])\n",
    "nw_m = len(dat.loc[np.logical_and(dat['region']=='northwest', np.logical_and(dat['smoker']=='yes', dat['sex']=='male')),:])\n",
    "nw_f = len(dat.loc[np.logical_and(dat['region']=='northwest', np.logical_and(dat['smoker']=='yes', \n",
    "                                                                                                 dat['sex']=='female')),:])\n",
    "ne_m = len(dat.loc[np.logical_and(dat['region']=='northeast', np.logical_and(dat['smoker']=='yes', dat['sex']=='male')),:])\n",

    "                                                                                                 dat['sex']=='female')),:])\n",
    "ratio = [round(sw_f/sw_m,3), round(se_f/se_m,3), round(nw_f/nw_m,3), round(ne_f/ne_m,3)]\n",

    "## Hypothesis Testing"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "af3e1df5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<b> Objective #1: Are medical claims made by smokers greater than those who don't smoke?\n",
    "\n",
    "H0:  μ1 ≤ μ2                                                                                                        \n",
    "Ha:  μ1 > μ2\n",
    " \n",
    "Where:\n",
    "\n",
    "μ1 = Claims by smokers                                                                                          \n",
    "μ2 = Claims by non-smokers\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.05     (95% Confidence Interval)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "id": "356f72ce",

    "ax1.axvline(np.median(x2),color='green',linestyle='--', label='median')\n",

    "plt.xticks(fontsize=14);\n",
    "plt.yticks(fontsize=14);\n",
    "plt.legend(fontsize=14);\n",
    "ax1.set_xticks(np.arange(0,80001,10000));"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e1a0672a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The non-smoker distribution is both positively skewed and highly leptokurtic on one-tail. The smoker distribution is slightly platykurtic (kurt -1). Let's attempt to transform the distributions to normal using the Box-Cox Transform."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "136deeee",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Box-Cox Transformation\n",
    "Since the distribution is significantly positively skewed for the non-smoker distribution, let's apply a Box-Cox transformation on both to get a more normal distribution and see if the data passes normality tests."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "id": "ee9dcb59",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 900x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

       "<Figure size 900x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Box-Cox transform of data\n",
    "tx1, _ = stats.boxcox(x1)      #insurance charges for smokers\n",
    "tx2, _ = stats.boxcox(x2)      #insurance charges for non-smokers\n",
    "\n",
    "# histogram of charges for smokers\n",
    "fig1 = plt.figure(figsize=[9,6]);\n",

    "ax1.axvline(np.median(tx2),color='green',linestyle='--', label='median')\n",

    "plt.xlabel('Charges [$USD]', fontsize='14', fontweight='bold');\n",

    "plt.xticks(fontsize=14);\n",
    "plt.yticks(fontsize=14);\n",
    "plt.legend(fontsize=14);\n",
    "ax1.set_xticks(np.arange(0,101,10));"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2674daa9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Box-Cox transform brought the skew of both distributions to near normality. It also brought the kurtosis closer to normality for the non-smoker distribution but slightly increased the platykurtosis of the smoker distribution. This is close enough to continue forward with hypothesis testing in this case."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "71ad11e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### First attempt: Two-Sample T-test\n",
    "\n",
    "A two sample T-test appears to be the appropriate test for this hypothesis because the population standard deviation is unknown and we are comparing two separate sample distributions.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### The assumptions of the two-sample t-test:\n",
    "\n",
    "- The data are continuous (not discrete).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- The data follow the normal probability distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- The variances of the two populations are equal. (If not, the Aspin-Welch Unequal-Variance test is used.)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- The two samples are independent. There is no relationship between the individuals in one sample as compared to the other (as there is in the paired t-test).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Both samples are simple random samples from their respective populations. Each individual in the population has an equal probability of being selected in the sample.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Here, we see that all assumptions are met except two: whether the data follows the normal probability distribution and whether the variances of the two populations are equal.\n",
    "\n",
    "Below, these assumptions are tested."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a415d6a4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Shapiro-Wilks and Anderson-Darling Test for Normality\n",
    "\n",
    "Will use the Shapiro-Wilks test and the Anderson-Darling test to determine whether the data is normally distributed. The hypothesis is as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "H0: The data is normally distributed\n",
    "Ha: The data is not normally distributed\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.01"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "id": "1641fb42",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Shapiro-Wilks test\n",
      "Charges by smokers:      p-value: 0.00000000\n",
      "Charges by non-smokers:  p-value: 0.00000000\n",
      "\n",
      "Anderson-Darling Test\n",
      "Charges by smokers:      Anderson-Darling statistic is 6.50 times the critical value for alpha = 0.01\n",
      "Charges by non-smokers:  Anderson-Darling statistic is 4.73 times the critical value for alpha = 0.01\n",
      "\n",
      "Number of samples:\n",
      "Charges by smokers:      n = 274\n",
      "Charges by non-smokers:  n = 1064\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# test for normality of sample data using both Shapiro-Wilks Test and Anderson-Darling Test\n",
    "statistic1, pval1 = stats.shapiro(tx1)\n",
    "statistic2, pval2 = stats.shapiro(tx2)\n",
    "astat1, crit1, sig1 = stats.anderson(tx1, dist='norm')\n",
    "astat2, crit2, sig2 = stats.anderson(tx2, dist='norm')\n",
    "# print results\n",
    "blah1 = astat1/crit1[4]\n",
    "blah2 = astat2/crit2[4]\n",
    "print(\"Shapiro-Wilks test\")\n",
    "print('Charges by smokers:      p-value: %.8f' % pval1)\n",
    "print('Charges by non-smokers:  p-value: %.8f' % pval2)\n",
    "print('\\nAnderson-Darling Test')\n",
    "print('Charges by smokers:      Anderson-Darling statistic is %.2f times the critical value for alpha = 0.01' % blah1)\n",
    "print('Charges by non-smokers:  Anderson-Darling statistic is %.2f times the critical value for alpha = 0.01' % blah2)\n",
    "print('\\nNumber of samples:')\n",
    "print('Charges by smokers:      n = {}' .format(len(x1)))\n",
    "print('Charges by non-smokers:  n = {}' .format(len(x2)))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "238f8bdc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "From the tests for normality performed above, it is demonstrated that the data violates the normality assumption for a two-sample t-test: both the p-values claculated using the Shapiro-Wilks test and the statistic calculated using Anderson-Darling test indicate a significant departure from normality. However, since the sample sizes of both sets of data are greater than 30 (n > 30), we will invoke the central limit theorem and proceed ahead with testing whether the variances of the two populations are equal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0fbd7f5f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Levene's Test for Equality of Variance\n",
    "\n",
    "H0: The variances are equal across all samples.\n",
    "Ha: The variances are not equal for at least one pair.\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.05\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we will use Levene's Test because the data failed Shapiro-Wilks test and Anderson-Darling's test. Levene's test is more robust with data that is found to not follow a normal distribution. If the samples had passed the Shapiro-Wilks test and Anderson-Darling's test, Bartlett's test for equality of variance is the more appropriate test."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "id": "6cad5970",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "\"use Levene's test for equality of variace because the data departs from normality, otherwise, \\n   we would have used Bartlett's test\""
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 40,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are not equal for at least one pair.\n",
      "p-value: 0.00000000\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "'''use Levene's test for equality of variace because the data departs from normality, otherwise, \n",
    "   we would have used Bartlett's test'''\n",
    "\n",
    "stat, pval = stats.levene(tx1, tx2, center='mean')\n",
    "\n",
    "if pval < 0.05:\n",
    "    print('Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are not equal for at least one pair.\\np-value: %.8f' % pval)\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print('Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are equal across all samples.\\np-value: %.8f' % pval)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "370cf4f6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It has been found that the sample data violates the assumption of equality of variance. A Welch's t-test (or unequal variance t-test) must be performed instead of a Student's two-sample t-test."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0abc10b7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Welch's One-tail, Two-Sample T-test\n",
    "If we recall, our Null and Alternative Hypotheses are:\n",
    "\n",
    "H0: μ1 ≤ μ2                                                                                                          \n",
    "Ha: μ1 > μ2\n",
    " \n",
    "Where:\n",
    "\n",
    "μ1 = Claims by smokers                                                                                              \n",
    "μ2 = Claims by non-smokers\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.05     (95% Confidence Interval)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "id": "170c8c75",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Reject Null Hypothesis: claims by smokers are statistically greater than claims by non-smokers.           \n",
      "p-value: 0.00000000\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#Perform Welch's two-sample t-test on log-transformed data\n",
    "statistic, pval = stats.ttest_ind(tx1, tx2, equal_var = False) \n",
    "# should use alternative='greater' in newer versions of scipy (>1.4.1). 1.4.1 does not allow anything but two-sided test.\n",
    "\n",
    "if pval1 < 0.05:\n",
    "    print('Reject Null Hypothesis: claims by smokers are statistically greater than claims by non-smokers.\\\n",
    "           \\np-value: %.8f' % pval1)\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print('Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis: claims by smokers are either statistically equal to or less than claims \\\n",
    "        by non-smokers.\\np-value: %.8f' % pval1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cf3f42fe",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Objective #2: Is the BMI of females different than the BMI of males?\n",

    "μ1 = BMI of females                                                                                                    \n",
    "μ2 = BMI of males\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.05     (95% Confidence Interval)"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5fd9181e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Shapiro-Wilks and Anderson-Darling Tests for Normality\n",
    "Will use the Shapiro-Wilks test and the Anderson-Darling test to determine whether the data is normally distributed. The hypothesis is as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "H0: The data is normally distributed                                                                        \n",
    "Ha: The data is not normally distributed\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.01"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 44,
   "id": "0e82274f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Shapiro-Wilks test\n",
      "BMI of females:  p-value: 0.00354337\n",
      "BMI of males:    p-value: 0.00313064\n",
      "\n",
      "Anderson-Darling Test\n",
      "BMI of females:  Anderson-Darling statistic is 0.75 times the critical value for alpha = 0.01\n",
      "BMI of males:    Anderson-Darling statistic is 0.58 times the critical value for alpha = 0.01\n",
      "\n",
      "Number of samples:\n",
      "BMI of females:  n = 662\n",
      "BMI of males:    n = 676\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# test for normality of sample data using both Shapiro-Wilks Test and Anderson-Darling Test\n",
    "statistic1, pval1 = stats.shapiro(x1)\n",
    "statistic2, pval2 = stats.shapiro(x2)\n",
    "astat1, crit1, sig1 = stats.anderson(x1, dist='norm')\n",
    "astat2, crit2, sig2 = stats.anderson(x2, dist='norm')\n",
    "#print results\n",
    "blah1 = astat1/crit1[4]\n",
    "blah2 = astat2/crit2[4]\n",
    "print(\"Shapiro-Wilks test\")\n",
    "print('BMI of females:  p-value: %.8f' % pval1)\n",
    "print('BMI of males:    p-value: %.8f' % pval2)\n",
    "print('\\nAnderson-Darling Test')\n",
    "print('BMI of females:  Anderson-Darling statistic is %.2f times the critical value for alpha = 0.01' % blah1)\n",
    "print('BMI of males:    Anderson-Darling statistic is %.2f times the critical value for alpha = 0.01' % blah2)\n",
    "print('\\nNumber of samples:')\n",
    "print('BMI of females:  n = {}' .format(len(x1)))\n",
    "print('BMI of males:    n = {}' .format(len(x2)))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "31d23d66",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here it is found that the distributions are approximately normal. While the p-value's calculated in Shapiro-Wilks test tend to non-normality, the Anderson-Darling statistics indicate otherwise. It's important to note that larger n values tend to bias these tests toward a finding of non-normality, so the interpretation of such tests requires more leniency when dealing with higher sample datasets. Also, visually the distributions appear approximately normal. Next we will test whether the variances of the two populations are equal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "064f3f0d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Bartlett's Test for Equality of Variance\n",
    "H0: The variances are equal across all samples.                                                        \n",
    "Ha: The variances are not equal for at least one pair.\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.05\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we will use Bartlett's test for equality of variance because the data was found to be approximately normal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 45,
   "id": "47e24e6c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are equal across all samples.\n",
      "p-value: 0.6890\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#use Bartlett's test for equality of variance because the data is approximately normal\n",
    "stat, pval = stats.bartlett(x1, x2)\n",
    "\n",
    "if pval < 0.05:\n",
    "    print('Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are not equal for at least one pair.\\np-value: %.4f' % pval)\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print('Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are equal across all samples.\\np-value: %.4f' % pval)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9f18cdd3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Two-Sample T-test\n",
    "A two sample T-test is the appropriate test for this hypothesis because all of the following assumptions are met:\n",
    "\n",
    "<b> The assumptions of the two-sample t-test:\n",
    "\n",
    "- The data are continuous (not discrete).\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "- The data follow the normal probability distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "- The variances of the two populations are equal. (If not, the Aspin-Welch Unequal-Variance test is used.)\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "- The two samples are independent. There is no relationship between the individuals in one sample as compared to the other (as there is in the paired t-test).\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "- Both samples are simple random samples from their respective populations. Each individual in the population has an equal probability of being selected in the sample."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "id": "95bf07c5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis: the BMI of females and the BMI of males are not statistically different.          \n",
      "p-value: 0.0900\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#Student's Two-Sample t-test\n",
    "statistic, pval = stats.ttest_ind(x1, x2, equal_var = True) \n",
    "if pval < 0.05:\n",
    "    print('Reject Null Hypothesis: the BMI of females is statistically different than the BMI of males.\\\n",
    "           \\np-value: %.4f' % pval)\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print('Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis: the BMI of females and the BMI of males are not statistically different.\\\n",
    "          \\np-value: %.4f' % pval)\n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "164085f9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Objective #3: Is the proportion of smokers significantly different across different regions?\n",
    "\n",
    "H0: There is no relationship between smoking and region                                                               \n",
    "Ha: There is a relationship between smoking and region\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.05     (95% Confidence Interval)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cbe4fd69",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Chi-Square Test of Independence\n",
    "\n",
    "The Chi-Square Test of Independence looks at whether there is a significant relationship between two categorical variables (in this case smoking and region). The frequency of each category of one categorical variable is compared across the categories of the other categorical variable. The assumptions for this test are that the sample is randomly drawn from the population and that all expected values are at least 5."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 47,
   "id": "c7fa2331",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [

       "        vertical-align: middle;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n",
       "        vertical-align: top;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe thead th {\n",
       "        text-align: right;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "</style>\n",
       "<table border=\"1\" class=\"dataframe\">\n",

       "smoke      non-smoker  smoker\n",

   ],
   "source": [
    "# get data in correct form to create a pandas crosstab\n",
    "reg = []\n",
    "smoke = []\n",
    "for i in np.arange(0,len(dat)):\n",
    "    if dat.loc[i,'region'] == 'northwest':\n",
    "        reg.append('northwest')\n",
    "        if dat.loc[i,'smoker'] == 'yes':\n",
    "            smoke.append('smoker')\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            smoke.append('non-smoker')\n",
    "    if dat.loc[i,'region'] == 'northeast':\n",
    "        reg.append('northeast')\n",
    "        if dat.loc[i,'smoker'] == 'yes':\n",
    "            smoke.append('smoker')\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            smoke.append('non-smoker')      \n",
    "    if dat.loc[i,'region'] == 'southwest':\n",
    "        reg.append('southwest')\n",
    "        if dat.loc[i,'smoker'] == 'yes':\n",
    "            smoke.append('smoker')\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            smoke.append('non-smoker')\n",
    "    if dat.loc[i,'region'] == 'southeast':\n",
    "        reg.append('southeast')\n",
    "        if dat.loc[i,'smoker'] == 'yes':\n",
    "            smoke.append('smoker')\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            smoke.append('non-smoker')\n",
    "ct = pd.DataFrame()\n",
    "ct['region'] = reg\n",
    "ct['smoke'] = smoke\n",
    "\n",
    "#create pandas crosstab\n",
    "cross = pd.crosstab(ct.region, ct.smoke)\n",
    "cross"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 50,
   "id": "829be716",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "statistic = 7.3435  |  p-value = 0.0617  |  DOF = 3\n",
      "\n",
      "Expected Values:       \n",
      "[[257.65022422  66.34977578]\n",
      " [258.44544096  66.55455904]\n",
      " [289.45889387  74.54110613]\n",
      " [258.44544096  66.55455904]]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Chi-square test of independence.\n",
    "c, p, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(cross)\n",
    "\n",
    "#contingency\n",
    "print('statistic = {}  |  p-value = {}  |  DOF = {}\\n\\nExpected Values:\\\n",
    "       \\n{}'.format(np.round(c, 4), np.round(p, 4), np.round(dof, 0), expected))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "285af1fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here, we fail to reject the Null Hypothesis (p-value = 0.06) and conclude that there is no relationship between smoking and region."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7cbe1f6f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Chi-Square Post-Hoc Analysis and Bonferroni Correction\n",
    "\n",
    "Next, a post-hoc analysis looking at the relationship between each region is performed. As there will be multiple hypothesis tests performed for this post-hoc analysis, the p-value needs to be corrected to compensate for the increased likelihood of type I error. This is done by applying the Bonferroni correction or by testing each individual hypothesis at a significance level of  α/m where α is the desired overall alpha level (here α = 0.05) and m is the number of hypotheses (here m = 6). The Bonferroni corrected p-value for this ad-hoc analysis, therefore, is 0.0083."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 52,
   "id": "d724c8e6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "northeast & northwest : statistic = 0.665  |  p-value = 0.4148  |  DOF = 1\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "northeast & southeast : statistic = 1.5731  |  p-value = 0.2098  |  DOF = 1\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "northeast & southwest : statistic = 0.665  |  p-value = 0.4148  |  DOF = 1\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "northwest & southeast : statistic = 4.771  |  p-value = 0.0289  |  DOF = 1\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "northwest & southwest : statistic = 0.0  |  p-value = 1.0  |  DOF = 1\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "southeast & southwest : statistic = 4.771  |  p-value = 0.0289  |  DOF = 1\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "c1, p1, dof1, expected1 = stats.chi2_contingency(cross.iloc[[0,1],:])\n",
    "c2, p2, dof2, expected2 = stats.chi2_contingency(cross.iloc[[0,2],:])\n",
    "c3, p3, dof3, expected3 = stats.chi2_contingency(cross.iloc[[0,3],:])\n",
    "c4, p4, dof4, expected4 = stats.chi2_contingency(cross.iloc[[1,2],:])\n",
    "c5, p5, dof5, expected5 = stats.chi2_contingency(cross.iloc[[1,3],:])\n",
    "c6, p6, dof6, expected6 = stats.chi2_contingency(cross.iloc[[2,3],:])\n",
    "\n",
    "# contingency\n",
    "print('northeast & northwest : statistic = {}  |  p-value = {}  |  DOF = {}\\n\\n'.format(np.round(c1, 4), np.round(p1, 4), \n",
    "                                                                                                       np.round(dof1, 0)))\n",

    "                                                                                                       np.round(dof2, 0)))\n",
    "print('northeast & southwest : statistic = {}  |  p-value = {}  |  DOF = {}\\n\\n'.format(np.round(c3, 4), np.round(p3, 4), \n",
    "                                                                                                       np.round(dof3, 0)))\n",
    "print('northwest & southeast : statistic = {}  |  p-value = {}  |  DOF = {}\\n\\n'.format(np.round(c4, 4), np.round(p4, 4), \n",
    "                                                                                                       np.round(dof4, 0)))\n",
    "print('northwest & southwest : statistic = {}  |  p-value = {}  |  DOF = {}\\n\\n'.format(np.round(c5, 4), np.round(p5, 4), \n",
    "                                                                                                       np.round(dof5, 0)))\n",
    "print('southeast & southwest : statistic = {}  |  p-value = {}  |  DOF = {}'.format(np.round(c6, 4), np.round(p6, 4), \n",
    "                                                                                                       np.round(dof6, 0)))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "12afaca6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As none of the p-values for the post-hoc tests fall below the bonferroni corrected p-value of 0.0083, there is no statistically significant relationship between region and smoking for any combination of regions."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# get data in correct form to create a pandas crosstab\n",
    "reg = []\n",
    "fem_sm = []\n",
    "for i in np.arange(0,len(dat)):\n",
    "    if dat.loc[i,'region'] == 'northwest':\n",
    "        reg.append('northwest')\n",
    "        if np.logical_and(dat.loc[i,'smoker'] == 'yes', dat.loc[i,'sex'] == 'female') == True:\n",
    "            fem_sm.append('female smoker')\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            fem_sm.append('not female smoker')\n",
    "    if dat.loc[i,'region'] == 'northeast':\n",
    "        reg.append('northeast')\n",
    "        if np.logical_and(dat.loc[i,'smoker'] == 'yes', dat.loc[i,'sex'] == 'female') == True:\n",
    "            fem_sm.append('female smoker')\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            fem_sm.append('not female smoker')      \n",
    "    if dat.loc[i,'region'] == 'southwest':\n",
    "        reg.append('southwest')\n",
    "        if np.logical_and(dat.loc[i,'smoker'] == 'yes', dat.loc[i,'sex'] == 'female') == True:\n",
    "            fem_sm.append('female smoker')\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            fem_sm.append('not female smoker')\n",
    "    if dat.loc[i,'region'] == 'southeast':\n",
    "        reg.append('southeast')\n",
    "        if np.logical_and(dat.loc[i,'smoker'] == 'yes', dat.loc[i,'sex'] == 'female') == True:\n",
    "            fem_sm.append('female smoker')\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            fem_sm.append('not female smoker')\n",
    "ct1 = pd.DataFrame()\n",
    "ct1['region'] = reg\n",
    "ct1['female_sm'] = fem_sm\n",
    "\n",
    "# create pandas crosstab\n",
    "cross2 = pd.crosstab(ct1.region, ct1.female_sm)\n",
    "cross2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 54,
   "id": "c346f536",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",

      "statistic = 2.7568  |  p-value = 0.4307  |  DOF = 3\n",
      "\n",
      "Expected Values:\n",
      "[[ 27.84753363 296.15246637]\n",
      " [ 27.93348281 297.06651719]\n",

      " [ 27.93348281 297.06651719]]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Chi-square test of independence.\n",
    "c2, p2, dof2, expected2 = stats.chi2_contingency(cross2)\n",
    "\n",
    "#contingency\n",
    "print('statistic = {}  |  p-value = {}  |  DOF = {}\\n\\nExpected Values:\\n{}'.format(np.round(c2, 4), np.round(p2, 4), \n",
    "                                                                                         np.round(dof2, 0), expected2))"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e9c38329",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Objective #4: Is the mean BMI of women with no children, one child, and two children the same?\n",
    "\n",
    "H0:  μ1 = μ2 = μ3                                                                                                   \n",
    "Ha:  μ1 ≠ μ2 | μ2 ≠ μ3 | μ1 ≠ μ3\n",
    " \n",
    "Where:\n",
    "\n",
    "μ1 = BMI of women with no children                                                                                     \n",
    "μ2 = BMI of women with one child                                                                                     \n",
    "μ3 = BMI of women with two children\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.05     (95% Confidence Interval)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 56,
   "id": "92ac9d4f",
   "metadata": {},

      ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1653d407",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### One-Way ANOVA\n",
    "Because the eqaulity of three population means will be tested, one-way ANOVA is the ideal test.\n",
    "\n",
    "<b> The assumptions of one-way ANOVA :\n",
    "\n",
    "- Residuals (experimental error) are normally distributed.\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "- Homogeneity of variances (variances are equal between treatment groups).\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "- Observations are sampled independently from each other"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4ea4a23c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Test for normality to determine which test for equality of variance to use.\n",
    "\n",
    "Will use Shapiro-Wilks and Anderson-Darling tests to determine whether the data is normally distributed. The hypothesis is as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "H0: The data is normally distributed                                                                                   \n",
    "Ha: The data is not normally distributed\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.01"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 58,
   "id": "0c0f3182",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Shapiro-Wilks test:\n",
      "BMI of females with no children:  p-value: 0.03757598\n",
      "BMI of females with 1 child:      p-value: 0.53619117\n",
      "BMI of females with 2 children:   p-value: 0.25962299\n",
      "\n",
      "Anderson-Darling Test:\n",
      "BMI of females with no children:  Anderson-Darling statistic is 0.76 times the critical value for alpha = 0.01\n",
      "BMI of females with 1 child:      Anderson-Darling statistic is 0.30 times the critical value for alpha = 0.01\n",
      "BMI of females with 2 children:   Anderson-Darling statistic is 0.36 times the critical value for alpha = 0.01\n",
      "\n",
      "Number of samples:\n",
      "BMI of females with no children:  n = 289\n",
      "BMI of females with 1 child:      n = 158\n",
      "BMI of females with 2 children:   n = 119\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# test for normality of sample data using both Shapiro-Wilks Test and Anderson-Darling Test\n",
    "statistic1, pval1 = stats.shapiro(x1)\n",
    "statistic2, pval2 = stats.shapiro(x2)\n",
    "statistic3, pval3 = stats.shapiro(x3)\n",
    "astat1, crit1, sig1 = stats.anderson(x1, dist='norm')\n",
    "astat2, crit2, sig2 = stats.anderson(x2, dist='norm')\n",
    "astat3, crit3, sig3 = stats.anderson(x3, dist='norm')\n",
    "\n",
    "# print results\n",
    "blah1 = astat1/crit1[4]\n",
    "blah2 = astat2/crit2[4]\n",
    "blah3 = astat3/crit3[4]\n",
    "print(\"Shapiro-Wilks test:\")\n",
    "print('BMI of females with no children:  p-value: %.8f' % pval1)\n",
    "print('BMI of females with 1 child:      p-value: %.8f' % pval2)\n",
    "print('BMI of females with 2 children:   p-value: %.8f' % pval3)\n",
    "print('\\nAnderson-Darling Test:')\n",
    "print('BMI of females with no children:  Anderson-Darling statistic is %.2f times the critical value for alpha = 0.01' \n",
    "                                                                                                                 % blah1)\n",
    "print('BMI of females with 1 child:      Anderson-Darling statistic is %.2f times the critical value for alpha = 0.01' \n",
    "                                                                                                                 % blah2)\n",
    "print('BMI of females with 2 children:   Anderson-Darling statistic is %.2f times the critical value for alpha = 0.01' \n",
    "                                                                                                                 % blah3)\n",
    "print('\\nNumber of samples:')\n",
    "print('BMI of females with no children:  n = {}' .format(len(x1)))\n",
    "print('BMI of females with 1 child:      n = {}' .format(len(x2)))\n",
    "print('BMI of females with 2 children:   n = {}' .format(len(x3)))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7d7b14c4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here it is found that the distributions are approximately normal. Both the p-values calculated using the Shapiro-Wilks test and the Anderson-Darling statistics support that conclusion. Also, visually, the distributions appear approximately normal. Next we will test whether the variances of the two populations are equal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2d14a7ff",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Bartlett's Test for Equality of Variance\n",
    "\n",
    "H0: The variances are equal across all samples.                                                                         \n",
    "Ha: The variances are not equal for at least one pair.\n",
    "\n",
    "α = 0.05\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we will use Bartlett's test for equality of variance because the data was found to be approximately normal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 59,
   "id": "36efbf84",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are equal across all samples.\n",
      "p-value: 0.2477\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#use Bartlett's test for equality of variance because the data is approximately normal\n",
    "stat, pval = stats.bartlett(x1, x2, x3)\n",
    "\n",
    "if pval < 0.05:\n",
    "    print('Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are not equal for at least one pair.\\np-value: %.4f' % pval)\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print('Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis: the variances are equal across all samples.\\np-value: %.4f' % pval)"
   ]
  },
  {

       "      <td>563.0</td>\n",

       "      <td>NaN</td>\n",
       "    </tr>\n",
       "  </tbody>\n",
       "</table>\n",
       "</div>"
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "                   sum_sq     df         F    PR(>F)\n",
       "C(children)     24.590123    2.0  0.334472  0.715858\n",
       "Residual     20695.661583  563.0       NaN       NaN"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 61,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mod = ols('bmi ~ C(children)', data = formulated).fit()\n",
    "aov = sm.stats.anova_lm(mod, typ='II')  \n",
    "aov"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e151a566",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Based upon the p-value of 0.71, the Null hypothesis is not rejected. It is concluded that the mean BMI of women with no children, one child, and two children are the same. The F-score generated from the ANOVA demonstrates that the variation of BMI between groups of women with no, 1, and 2 children is approximately  1/3rd the variation within the groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's perform some post-hoc analyses to verify the results:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "26c279f5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Test for Normality of Residuals.\n",
    "\n",
    "Will look at Jarque-Bera Test, Chi-Square Test for Normality, Skew, and Kurtosis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 62,
   "id": "2cca7d4f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Jarque-Bera: 6.6710\n",
      "Chi-Square:  0.0356\n",
      "Skew:        0.2340\n",
      "Kurtosis:    2.7471\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "name = ['Jarque-Bera', 'Chi^2 two-tail prob.', 'Skew', 'Kurtosis']\n",
    "test = sms.jarque_bera(mod.resid)\n",
    "print('Jarque-Bera: %.4f' % test[0])\n",
    "print('Chi-Square:  %.4f' % test[1])\n",
    "print('Skew:        %.4f' % test[2])\n",
    "print('Kurtosis:    %.4f' % test[3])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aed44f1a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<b> Observation:\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite a high Jarque-Bera statistic (should be near 1 for normal distribution of residuals), the p-value for the Chi-square test for normality (< 0.05) and both skew and kurtosis indicate that the residuals are approximately normally distributed (a normal distribution has a skew of 0 and kurtosis of 3). Based on the results, the Null hypothesis is accepted: the residuals are normally distributed, meeting the assumption of one-way ANOVA."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4f293074",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Tukey's Range Function (aka Honest Significant Difference test)\n",
    "\n",
    "- The observations being tested are independent within and among the groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- The groups associated with each mean in the test are normally distributed.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- There is equal within-group variance across the groups associated with each mean in the test (homogeneity of variance).\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "These assumptions have already been verified so the test will proceed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 63,
   "id": "d0d1e746",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Multiple Comparison of Means - Tukey HSD, FWER=0.05\n",
      "===================================================\n",
      "group1 group2 meandiff p-adj   lower  upper  reject\n",
      "---------------------------------------------------\n",
      "     0      1  -0.3089 0.8641 -1.7185 1.1008  False\n",
      "     0      2   0.2883 0.9003 -1.2636 1.8401  False\n",
      "     1      2   0.5971 0.6961 -1.1322 2.3265  False\n",
      "---------------------------------------------------\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "tukey = pairwise_tukeyhsd(endog=formulated['bmi'], groups=formulated['children'], alpha=0.05)\n",
    "print(tukey)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8e02e9e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The results of Tukey's range function demonstrate that all group means are statistically the same with p-values:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Between no child and 1 child females:   p-value = 0.8494\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "- Between no child and 2 child females:   p-value = 0.8942\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "- Between 1 child and 2 child females:     p-value = 0.6797"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "116818d4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "- Smoking and obesity appear to be the greatest contributors to higher cost insurance claims, with comorbidity resulting in substantially higher insurance claims than one or the other.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Claims by smokers are statistically greater than claims by non-smokers.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Obesity is a problem for both males and females and there is not a statistical difference in the mean between both groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- There is not a statistical difference in the proportion of smokers by region, nor does gender affect smoking by region.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Having children does not affect the BMI of females, as there is no statistical difference in the mean BMI of females with no child, 1 child, or two children."
